Matt Connors, 'Untitled', 2015, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Acknowledging the influence of Abstract Expressionism, Arte Povera, and Henri Matisse, Matt Connors also draws from language, music, and design to create paintings that seem simultaneously familiar and new. Foil (2011) for instance, evokes the crescent shapes and primary colors of Joan Miró, but with a confounding haziness described by one critic in Artforum as "somewhere between a bumpy sfumato and the signature spray of graffiti."

Chris Martin, 'Dedicated to Blinky Palermo, 1973-2005', 1973-2005, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Signature: signed with the artist's initials, titled and dated "DEDICATED TO BLINKY PALERMO 1975-2005 CM" along the lower edge; further signed, initialed and dated "C MARTIN 1973-2005 CM" on the reverse

Yves Klein, 'Table Bleue', Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Yves Klein is best known for his trademark ultramarine pigment, which he patented as International Klein Blue in 1961. "Blue...is beyond dimensions, whereas the other colors are not," he said. "All colors arouse specific ideas, while blue suggests at most the sea and the sky; and they, after all, are in actual, visible nature what is most abstract."

Fred Wilson, 'Portrait of S.A.M.', 1993, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Seattle Art Museum, Fred Wilson: The Museum: Mixed Metaphors, January 28 - June 13, 1993, pp.

Otto Zitko, 'Untitled', 2000, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Ellsworth Kelly, 'Untitled', 1987, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Characterized by an extreme economy of means, the works that comprise Ellsworth Kelly's highly-regarded practice reveal the artist's keen interest in formal issues such as ground/foreground, planarity, shape, and line. This particular drawing is uniquely notable both as a brilliant juxtaposition of naturalistic plant drawing and hard edged abstraction, and also as the maquette for the cover of the original catalogue raisonné of Kelly's prints.

Richard Deacon, 'Coat', 1990, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Using ceramics, stainless steel, and wood, 1987 Turner Prize winner Richard Deacon makes monumental sculptures that explore the nature of opposites. Deacon questions essential yet contradictory characteristics: rigidity and strength, the organic and the geometric, grace and awkwardness.

Elad Lassry, 'Beets', 2010, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Rob Wynne, 'Ampersand', ca. 2005, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Rob Wynne tests the boundaries of kitsch and beauty, sappiness and profundity in his delicately crafted mixed-media objects, installations, drawings, and canvases. Though he uses a range of techniques and mediums, hand-blown glass is central to his work.

James Rosenquist, 'Below the Equator, Above the Equator', 1975, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Leading Pop artist James Rosenquist-who came to prominence among New York School figures like Roy Lichtenstein, Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg, and Willem de Kooning-is well known for his large-scale, fragmented works that bring the visual language of commercial painting onto canvas (notably, from 1957-60, Rosenquist earned his living as a billboard painter).

Hans-Peter Feldmann, 'Pictures of car radios taken while good music was playing', Conceived in 1970s -1990s and executed in 2004, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

After winning the Guggenheim's 2010 Hugo Boss Prize, Hans-Peter Feldmann famously cashed his $100,000 check and pinned it in dollar bills to the museum's walls, raising questions about the value of art.

Adrian Paci, 'Facades', 2006, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Sterling Ruby, 'Headless Dick/Deth Till', 2008, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

Sterling Ruby, a multidisciplinary artist who makes urethane and bronze sculptures, hallucinatory color-field canvases, and handmade ceramics, addresses the conflict between individual desire and social structure, and the influence of institutional architecture, both literal and figurative, on human behavior and psychology.

Retna, 'Untitled (Rockin it sucker)', 2010, Phillips: New Now | Artsy

The street and studio artist Retna, born Marquis Lewis, picked his moniker from the lyrics of a Wu Tang song that resonated with him in his youth. Retna explains that he was inspired to pursue art after seeing graffiti on the freeway, and his practice now includes street art and painting on canvas.

Chicago (Trees in Snow) by Harry Callahan on artnet Auctions

Chicago (Trees in Snow) is one of Harry Callahan's most iconic works, depicting stark, black trees against a winter landscape along Chicago's Lake Shore Drive. Hand printed by Callahan, this photograph is an especially high-quality, rare print. It is incredibly detailed, and elements such as the grass peeking through the snow and the lake in the distance are visible in this print.
